<broken_object_property_level_authorization_guide>
<title>BROKEN OBJECT PROPERTY LEVEL AUTHORIZATION (OWASP API #3)</title>

<critical>BOPLA occurs when APIs expose sensitive object properties that users should not access or modify. Unlike BOLA (object-level), this affects individual fields within authorized objects—users can read/write properties beyond their privilege scope. Focus on mass assignment, excessive data exposure, and field-level authorization gaps.</critical>

<scope>
- Excessive data exposure in API responses (admin flags, internal IDs, PII)
- Mass assignment via property injection (isAdmin, role, balance, status)
- Unauthorized property modification in UPDATE/PATCH operations
- Nested object property access control gaps
- GraphQL field-level authorization bypass
- Response filtering and projection bypass
- JSON/XML property injection in write operations
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Enumerate all object properties in API responses—look for sensitive fields (role, balance, email, tokens, internal IDs)
2. Test read authorization: attempt to request sensitive fields via query params, GraphQL field selection, or projection operators
3. Test write authorization: inject unauthorized properties in POST/PUT/PATCH (isAdmin=true, role=admin, balance=1000000)
4. Compare responses between privileged and unprivileged accounts—diff the property sets
5. Test nested object properties and array element access control
6. Validate server-side filtering vs client-side filtering (bypass by removing filters)
</methodology>

<detection_surfaces>
<read_side>
- API responses containing more properties than UI displays (excess data exposure)
- Admin/internal properties visible in low-privilege responses: isAdmin, role, permissions[], internalId, systemNotes
- PII leakage: email, phone, address when only name should be visible
- Sensitive nested properties: user.paymentMethods[].cardNumber, organization.billingDetails
- Debug/metadata fields in production: _meta, _debug, _sql, createdBy, modifiedBy
- Aggregate data when only specific fields authorized: /users returns full profiles vs just names
</read_side>

<write_side>
- Mass assignment in user registration/update: inject {"isAdmin": true, "role": "admin"}
- Property injection in PATCH/PUT: modify read-only fields (balance, credits, verified, approved)
- Nested property modification: user.permissions[0].scope, user.settings.isFeatureEnabled
- Array manipulation: add admin roles to roles[], modify paymentMethods[] ownership
- Status/state manipulation: change order.status, ticket.priority without authorization
- Relationship injection: assign userId to objects, modify ownerId, change parent references
</write_side>
</detection_surfaces>

<testing_techniques>
<excessive_data_exposure>
- Compare API response properties to UI rendered fields—excess indicates potential leak
- Check different HTTP methods on same endpoint: GET vs POST may return different property sets
- Test with different Accept headers: application/json vs application/xml may expose different fields
- Query parameter projection: ?fields=*, ?select=*, ?include=* to request all properties
- Version testing: older API versions (v1 vs v2) may have different filtering
- Error responses: may contain full object dumps with sensitive properties
</excessive_data_exposure>

<mass_assignment>
- Register/create operations: inject extra properties in POST body
  POST /api/users {"username": "test", "email": "test@test.com", "isAdmin": true, "role": "admin"}
- Update operations: add unauthorized fields to PATCH/PUT
  PATCH /api/users/123 {"name": "New Name", "balance": 1000000, "verified": true}
- Nested injection: {"user": {"profile": {"name": "Test"}, "permissions": {"admin": true}}}
- Array manipulation: {"roles": ["user", "admin"], "groups": [1, 2, 999]}
- Type confusion: send objects where primitives expected to bypass validation
</mass_assignment>

<graphql_specific>
- Request all fields explicitly in query to detect missing field-level auth
  query { user(id: 123) { id name email phone ssn isAdmin role salary } }
- Use inline fragments to access interface/union fields without auth
- Bypass via aliases: query { user1: user(id: 1) { isAdmin } user2: user(id: 2) { isAdmin } }
- Introspection to enumerate all available fields, then request sensitive ones
- Nested queries to access related object properties: user { orders { internalNotes creditCardLast4 } }
- Mutation testing: try setting all fields in update mutations
</graphql_specific>

<filtering_bypass>
- Remove client-side projection: API sends ?fields=name,email but remove filter to get all
- Default projection: omit fields param to get full object instead of filtered view
- Wildcard projection: ?fields=* or ?select=* to override whitelist
- ORM/query builder leaks: some frameworks expose internal field filters that can be manipulated
- Content negotiation: XML vs JSON vs form-encoded may have different filter rules
</filtering_bypass>
</testing_techniques>

<property_targets>
<authentication_authorization>
- isAdmin, isActive, isVerified, emailVerified, phoneVerified
- role, roles[], permissions[], scopes[], authorities[]
- accessLevel, privilegeLevel, accountType, userType
- canEdit, canDelete, canApprove, isOwner, isModerator
- banned, suspended, locked, disabled
</authentication_authorization>

<financial_sensitive>
- balance, credits, points, wallet, accountBalance
- paymentMethods[], cards[], bankAccounts[]
- transactions[], payments[], invoices[]
- discountRate, pricing, cost, internalPrice
- commission, revenue, profit, earning
</financial_sensitive>

<pii_confidential>
- email, phone, address, ssn, taxId, dob, birthDate
- fullName vs displayName (may contain real name when only public name should be visible)
- ipAddress, userAgent, deviceId, sessionId
- location, gps, coordinates, lastLogin, loginHistory
- securityQuestions, recoveryEmail, backupEmail
</pii_confidential>

<internal_metadata>
- internalId, systemId, legacyId, externalId
- createdBy, modifiedBy, deletedBy, approvedBy
- createdAt, updatedAt, deletedAt (soft delete visibility)
- version, revision, changeLog, auditLog
- _meta, _debug, _sql, _internal, _system
- apiKey, secretKey, token, refreshToken, accessToken
</internal_metadata>
</property_targets>

<rest_specific>
<http_method_property_exposure>
- GET may filter properties, but POST/PUT on same endpoint may return unfiltered
- OPTIONS may expose all available properties in schema
- HEAD responses may include property names in headers
- DELETE may return full object before deletion
</http_method_property_exposure>

<query_parameter_abuse>
- ?fields=admin,role,balance to request sensitive fields
- ?expand=* or ?include=* to include nested sensitive objects
- ?debug=true or ?verbose=true may disable filtering
- ?format=full or ?view=admin to change response projection
- ?version=internal or ?mode=debug to access unfiltered endpoints
</query_parameter_abuse>

<path_variations>
- /api/users/123 vs /api/users/123/admin vs /api/users/123?view=admin
- /api/v1/users/123 (old version) vs /api/v2/users/123 (new version with better filtering)
- /api/public/users/123 vs /api/internal/users/123
</path_variations>
</rest_specific>

<validation_bypass>
<server_side_gaps>
- Validation only on specific properties but not all—inject new properties to bypass
- Whitelist validation that checks presence but not values—set isAdmin to true passes if isAdmin is allowed
- Type coercion: send "isAdmin": "true" (string) vs "isAdmin": true (boolean)
- Null/undefined handling: send null values to reset properties or bypass validation
- Array/object injection where primitive expected: {"role": {"$ne": "user"}} in NoSQL
</server_side_gaps>

<client_side_reliance>
- UI only shows name/email but API returns full user object—client filters, server doesn't
- Modify client code to request additional fields or remove filtering
- Intercept and modify API responses to see hidden properties
- Compare mobile app API calls to web app—different property sets may be exposed
</client_side_reliance>
</validation_bypass>

<impact_scenarios>
<privilege_escalation>
- Set isAdmin=true, role=admin to gain administrative access
- Modify permissions[] array to grant unauthorized scopes
- Change accountType from free to premium
- Bypass approval workflows by setting approved=true, status=approved
</privilege_escalation>

<data_exposure>
- Read other users' PII: email, phone, address, payment info
- Access internal identifiers that enable further attacks (IDOR)
- Retrieve API keys, tokens, secrets from user objects
- View audit logs, system notes, internal comments
</data_exposure>

<financial_fraud>
- Increase account balance, credits, points
- Modify pricing, discounts, commission rates
- Change payment method ownership
- Alter transaction history or amounts
</financial_fraud>
</impact_scenarios>

<validation>
1. Prove property exposure: show sensitive property in response that should not be visible to current user
2. Demonstrate write capability: modify unauthorized property and show server accepted it
3. Verify persistence: modified property remains changed on subsequent reads
4. Show impact: privilege escalation (isAdmin), financial gain (balance), or PII access
5. Compare with authorized user: same operation succeeds without injection for admin
6. Test multiple endpoints: ensure vulnerability is not isolated to single endpoint
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Properties visible but not sensitive (public profile fields)
- Properties returned but ignored/masked by proper frontend (server sends, UI doesn't render)
- Test/development environments with debug mode enabled (not production behavior)
- Properties writable but validated on business logic layer (attempt rejected despite acceptance)
- Public APIs intended to expose full object for legitimate reasons
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Horizontal privilege escalation: read/modify other users' sensitive properties
- Vertical privilege escalation: grant admin rights, bypass approval workflows
- Financial fraud: manipulate balances, pricing, payment information
- PII breach: access confidential personal/financial data
- Business logic bypass: modify state/status to skip workflows
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always diff API responses vs UI display—excess properties are reconnaissance gold
2. Test mass assignment on every write endpoint—inject isAdmin, role, balance systematically
3. GraphQL field enumeration via introspection reveals all properties—request them all
4. Compare responses between different user privilege levels—admin sees what regular users shouldn't
5. Nested objects often lack property-level checks—go deep into object hierarchies
6. Arrays of objects are commonly under-validated—inject into nested array elements
7. Version differences (v1 vs v2) may have different property filters—test all versions
8. Error responses and debug modes bypass filters—trigger errors intentionally
9. ORM frameworks expose more properties than intended—understand the ORM in use
10. Test with different Accept/Content-Type headers—XML/JSON/form may have different validation
11. Remove client-side projections—omit ?fields= to get default (often full object)
12. Status/state properties are high-value targets—approved, verified, active, enabled
</pro_tips>

<remember>Property-level authorization must be enforced server-side for both reads and writes. Whitelist exactly which properties each user role can access/modify, and validate on every operation regardless of client filtering.</remember>
</broken_object_property_level_authorization_guide>
